@node Introduction "MemUtil Documentation - Introduction"

MemUtil is a collection of some utilities I've written in the last years that
all have to do with memory stuff.

There is

· @{" ClearMem " link clearmem} - a utility to clear all free memory
· @{" MemSpeed " link memspeed}  - a utility to measure the read/write speed of memory
· @{" MemTest " link memtest}  - a utility to test memory for defects
· @{" NoMem " link nomem}    - a utility to make certain memory types unavailable to the system (like NoFastMem)

All utilities have in common, that they are doing stuff not completely 'legal' to system
software. So please @{b}don't@{ub} use these utilities together with other software, or
you may suffer data loss.

NoMem and ClearMem are mostly harmless, MemTest is a little bit nastier and MemSpeed
is doing some very nasty things (it stops the multitasking for a while, this can cause
data loss with serial transmissions).

So always keep my warnings in mind!

Created using SAS/C 6.58.

@endnode

@node clearmem "MemUtil Documentation - ClearMem"

@{u}ClearMem@{uu}

ClearMem is a tool that can set certain memory areas to the value 0 (zero). This
is sometimes helpful when you're searching data in memory: Usually freed memory
areas are not cleared, so there's a lot of trash in memory. By clearing memory
before loading the data, you have only the really important parts of your
data in memory (e.g. sounds, modules, pictures, etc.).

The usage of ClearMem is very simple. It supports the following options:


@{b}· CHIP/S@{ub} - clear all CHIP memory.
@{b}· FAST/S@{ub} - clear all FAST memory.
@{b}· ALL/S@{ub} - clear all memory.

@{b}Warning:@{ub} ClearMem has got to allocate large amounts of memory at once. In some
situations there's not enough memory left for the system and your computer can
@{b}CRASH@{ub}! This is not my fault, this is the fault of badly written software
that doesn't handle memory problems correctly.

@endnode

@node memspeed "MemUtil Documentation - MemSpeed"

@{u}MemSpeed@{uu}

MemSpeed is a utility to measure the speed of your memory. The speed is given
in the unit seconds per operation. MemSpeed won't try to give you theoretical
or practical usable values. MemSpeed values are MemSpeed values, nothing less
and nothing more.

MemSpeed measures the time the processor needs to read/write data without/with
cache with byte, word and longword data sizes.

@{b}Warning:@{ub} to give you better results, MemSpeed @{i}will@{ui}
turn off multitasking for a while, and you computer won't give you
live signs for this period! So better run this program alone!
  
MemSpeed supports the following options:

@{b}· MEMTYPE/K@{ub} - specification of the memory to use. This
    can be any combination of the words @{i}Chip, Fast, 24BitDMA, Local, Kick@{ui}
    and @{i}Public@{ui}. You can use any sepearator between two of these
    words, preferably '|'. Example: MEMTYPE="Chip|24BitDMA|Local"

@{b}· ADDRESS/K@{ub} - since the MEMTYPE specification is not very precise, you
    can alternatively use the ADDRESS keyword, followed by a @{i}hexadecimal@{ui}
    address. The address must be in the range available to the system. The best
    way to get such an address is to look at the memory types with the option
    LISTMEM first, and then use a 'Lower' address value with this argument.
    The address given is just a hint for the program in which memory region
    to allocate memory - it won't try to allocate memory at exactly the
    given address!
    Example: ADDRESS=00002000  will hopefully ;) be somewhere in your
        chip memory.
@{b}· LISTMEM/S@{ub} - list all available memory types.

@endnode


@node memtest "MemUtil Documentation - MemTest"

@{u}MemTest@{uu}

MemTest is a utility to perform memory tests. This can be very helpful when you have
some memory boards with defective memory and want to check them.

@{u}Note:@{uu} the memory you want to test MUST be available to the system! Otherwise
MemTest won't find it. This is a little bit difficult, since you have to get
MemTest's code in safe memory. Under some circumstances the system notices
itself that memory is defective and gives you a bus error or something like
that.

The usage of MemTest is quite easy:

@{b}· MEMTYPE/K@{ub} - specification of the memory to use. This
    can be any combination of the words @{i}Chip, Fast, 24BitDMA, Local, Kick@{ui}
    and @{i}Public@{ui}. You can use any sepearator between two of these
    words, preferably '|'. Example: MEMTYPE="Chip|24BitDMA|Local"

@{b}· ITERATIONS/N@{ub} - the number of test iterations to perform. With this
    option you can do a long time test with your memory to see whether you have
    thermical problems.

@{b}· ADDRESS/K@{ub} - since the MEMTYPE specification is not very precise, you
    can alternatively use the ADDRESS keyword, followed by a @{i}hexadecimal@{ui}
    address. The address must be in the range available to the system. The best
    way to get such an address is to look at the memory types with the option
    LISTMEM first, and then use a 'Lower' address value with this argument.
    The address given is just a hint for the program in which memory region
    to allocate memory - it won't try to allocate memory at exactly the
    given address!
    Example: ADDRESS=00002000  will hopefully ;) be somewhere in your
        chip memory.

@{b}· FORBID/S@{ub} - forbid multitasking while doing memory testings. This
    is usually not nescessary.

@{b}· LISTMEM/S@{ub} - list all available memory types.


@endnode


@node nomem "MemUtil Documentation - NoMem"

@{u}NoMem@{uu}

NoMem is a utility to remove certain types of memories from the system memory pool.
This is sometimes needed if

· you are running badly programmed software
· you want to force some software to load in a certain range of memory
· you have defective memory boards


NoMem supports the following command line arguments:

@{b}· CHIP/S@{ub} - remove all free CHIP memory from system memory. This can
    be dangerous since some graphics functions require chip memory and will
    crash without (not my fault - badly written software).

@{b}· FAST/S@{ub} - remove all free FAST memory from system memory.

@{b}· 24BITDMA/S@{ub} - remove all free 24BITDMA memory from system memory.
    This usually includes all chip memory. See the option CHIP for further
    notices. Using this option with the FAST option is safe (CHIP memory
    is granted not to be FAST memory).

@{b}· KICK/S@{ub} - remove all free KICK memory from system memory.
    See 24BITDMA for a warning about using this option alone.

@{b}· LOCAL/S@{ub} - remove all free FAST memory from system memory.
    See 24BITDMA for a warning about using this option alone.

@{b}· ALL/S@{ub} - remove all free FAST memory from system memory.
    This is very dangerous since even system software depends on some
    free memory (i.e. Intuition IDCMP messages).

@endnode

 
@node Usage "MemUtil Documentation - Usage"

@{b}MemUtil@{ub} is a packacke that can ony be used from Shell.

MemUtil consists of 4 programs:

· @{" ClearMem " link clearmem} - a utility to clear all free memory
· @{" MemSpeed " link memspeed}  - a utility to measure the read/write speed of memory
· @{" MemTest " link memtest}  - a utility to test memory for defects
· @{" NoMem " link nomem}    - a utility to make certain memory types unavailable to the system (like NoFastMem)

All programs were written some long time ago. For further usage information, please
follow the links to the programs. All programs were written in ANSI-C
with 68000 assembly code in the time cricital parts. I hope the programs
work on a plain 68000 Amiga, I didn't have the time to test this.

The programs all use system lists that are @{b}private@{ub} to the operating system.
Using these programs is always a risk! Be sure to know what you're doing
before you start one of them. Check your command line options twice!
Under some circumstances it's very likely that you crash your system
when using certain command line options. Using one of the programs
permanently as part of your system setup is no good idea...

The timings and values of all programs are neither meant to be realistic
in a theoretical or practical point of view. Just see these values as
part of the MemUtil package. If someone calculates the speed of memory
with the formula 1/(random access time) he'll soon find out that he's
a little bit wrong. 1/(random cycle time) is a better value, but it's
still not very realistic because it doesn't include the CPU overhead,
CPU speed, bus overhead, bus usage, ...
So please don't compare values from one system with another!

@endnode

